data.sampled: The gear ratio for the stepper motor can be calculated by dividing the number of teeth on the driver pinion gear by the number of teeth on the driven gear. Assuming that the driven gear is attached directly to the shaft of the stepper motor and has a diameter of 16 mm, then it would have a circumference of approximately 30 mm (pi x radius). If we assume an average step angle of 1.8 degrees for a typical 28 BYJ series stepper motor, then we can calculate the arc length over which the driven gear rotates as: Arc Length = Step Angle x Circumferencture. This gives us an arc length of about 5.4 mm (1.8 deg x 30 mm), which corresponds to roughly 16 steps per revolution (360 deg / 5.4 mm) .

data.sampled: The MVR series is rated for up to 10 Watts so this is within its rating and will have a tolerance of +/-5% which gives us a range from 6.35W (95%) to 8.64W (105%). This power rating is equivalent to a resistivity of about 2 ohm-cm but the exact value depends on how closely it is bonded to the heatsink. It can be as high as 1/10th that if it's well bonded or 10 times worse if it isn't. Assuming an average of 5 we get a resistance of 4 ohms. Using Joule's law (P = RI^2) and plugging in the numbers we find that it will dissipate an average of 1.6 watts. To raise the temperature by 50 degrees C it would need 0.8 calories per gram and since calories are equivalent to joules divided by 4.18 we find that it needs 0.8 / 4.18 * 1.6 = 0.394 watts per gram.
